## Comprehensive Request/Operation Logging in Gin

### What already exists

Gin's logging infrastructure is almost entirely self-contained in **`logger.go`**, wired into the handler chain via **`gin.go`**. The key moving parts:

| File | Symbol | Line | Role |
|---|---|---|---|
| `logger.go` | `LoggerConfig` | 39–59 | Configuration struct |
| `logger.go` | `LogFormatterParams` | 68–91 | Data bag passed to formatter |
| `logger.go` | `LoggerWithConfig` | 245–314 | Middleware factory — wraps `c.Next()` |
| `logger.go` | `defaultLogFormatter` | ~161 | Text formatter used by default |
| `context.go` | `Context.Next()` | 188–196 | Advances the handler chain |
| `context.go` | `Context.Set/Get` | 276–293 | Request-scoped key/value store |
| `context.go` | `Context.Error()` | 252–268 | Attaches an error to the context |
| `response_writer.go` | `Status()` / `Size()` | 98–104 | Response code and bytes written |
| `gin.go` | `Engine.Use()` | 340–345 | Registers global middleware |
| `gin.go` | `handleHTTPRequest` | 690–760 | Sets `c.handlers` + calls `c.Next()` |

The existing `LoggerWithConfig` captures: timestamp, latency, client IP, method, status code, path (with optional query), body size, and `ErrorTypePrivate` errors. It does **not** capture: request ID, matched route pattern, user-agent, request headers, request body, response headers, or structured (JSON) output.

---

### Gaps and what to add

#### 1. `logger.go` — Extend `LogFormatterParams` (lines 68–91)

The struct is the central data bag. Add these fields directly after `BodySize int`:

```go
// FullPath is the matched route pattern (e.g. /users/:id), distinct from the
// raw URL path. Empty for 404/405 responses.
FullPath string

// RequestID is the correlation/trace ID read from a header or generated.
RequestID string

// UserAgent is the client's User-Agent value.
UserAgent string

// RequestSize is the incoming body size in bytes (-1 if unknown).
RequestSize int64
```

#### 2. `logger.go` — Extend `LoggerConfig` (lines 39–59)

```go
// RequestIDHeader names the HTTP header used as a correlation ID.
// The value is read from the incoming request (or from c.Keys if a
// RequestID middleware ran first). Set to "" to disable.
// Default: "X-Request-ID"
RequestIDHeader string

// LogRequestHeaders is a list of request header names to capture.
// Values are stored in LogFormatterParams.Keys as "header:<Name>".
LogRequestHeaders []string
```

#### 3. `logger.go` — Update `LoggerWithConfig` (lines 245–314)

Inside the returned closure, after `c.Next()` and before populating `param`, add:

```go
param.FullPath = c.FullPath()     // matched route pattern
param.UserAgent = c.Request.UserAgent()
param.RequestSize = c.Request.ContentLength

if conf.RequestIDHeader != "" {
    // Prefer value set by a RequestID middleware via c.Set()
    if id, ok := c.Get(conf.RequestIDHeader); ok {
        param.RequestID, _ = id.(string)
    } else {
        param.RequestID = c.Request.Header.Get(conf.RequestIDHeader)
    }
}

for _, h := range conf.LogRequestHeaders {
    if param.Keys == nil {
        param.Keys = make(map[any]any)
    }
    param.Keys["header:"+h] = c.Request.Header.Get(h)
}
```

`c.FullPath()` is defined on `Context` (backed by `c.fullPath` set at `gin.go:712` inside `handleHTTPRequest`).  
`c.Request.UserAgent()` and `c.Request.ContentLength` are standard `net/http` fields — no new imports.

#### 4. `logger.go` — Add a structured (JSON) formatter

This is a new exported variable alongside `defaultLogFormatter`:

```go
// StructuredLogFormatter emits one JSON object per request, suitable for
// log aggregators (Datadog, Loki, CloudWatch, etc.).
var StructuredLogFormatter LogFormatter = func(p LogFormatterParams) string {
    entry := map[string]any{
        "time":       p.TimeStamp.Format(time.RFC3339Nano),
        "status":     p.StatusCode,
        "latency_ms": p.Latency.Milliseconds(),
        "client_ip":  p.ClientIP,
        "method":     p.Method,
        "path":       p.Path,
        "full_path":  p.FullPath,
        "body_bytes": p.BodySize,
    }
    if p.RequestID != ""  { entry["request_id"] = p.RequestID }
    if p.UserAgent != ""  { entry["user_agent"] = p.UserAgent }
    if p.RequestSize >= 0 { entry["request_bytes"] = p.RequestSize }
    if p.ErrorMessage != "" { entry["error"] = p.ErrorMessage }
    for k, v := range p.Keys {
        entry[fmt.Sprintf("ctx.%v", k)] = v
    }
    b, _ := json.Marshal(entry)
    return string(b) + "\n"
}
```

Requires adding `"encoding/json"` to the import block in `logger.go` (currently only uses `fmt`, `io`, `os`, `time` plus isatty).

#### 5. `logger.go` — Add a `RequestID` middleware factory

New exported function alongside `Logger`, `Recovery`, `ErrorLogger`:

```go
// RequestID returns a middleware that reads or generates a per-request
// correlation ID, stores it in c.Keys[header], and echoes it in the response.
// Use with LoggerConfig.RequestIDHeader set to the same header name.
func RequestID(header string) HandlerFunc {
    if header == "" {
        header = "X-Request-ID"
    }
    return func(c *Context) {
        id := c.Request.Header.Get(header)
        if id == "" {
            var b [8]byte
            if _, err := rand.Read(b[:]); err == nil {
                id = fmt.Sprintf("%x", b)
            }
        }
        c.Set(header, id)
        c.Header(header, id)
        c.Next()
    }
}
```

Requires `"crypto/rand"` import. `c.Set` is defined at `context.go:276`, `c.Header` at `context.go:~1080`.

